    "title": "Circulation Emergencies5",
    "content": "\"Soft Signs\" of a Heart Attack\nDuring a heart attack, many females, elderly people, and people with\ndiabetes tend to experience \"soft signs,\" which are milder or more\ngeneralized than the \"classic\" signs and symptoms of a heart attack.\nThese \"soft signs\" may be experienced for hours, days, or even weeks\nprior to the heart attack and are often dismissed as nothing out of the\n\"Soft signs\" include:\n• Mild, unfocused chest discomfort that:\n¶Comes and goes\n¶Does not necessarily feel painful\n¶Gets better with rest and worse with activity, or gets\nprogressively worse\n• Extreme fatigue (tiredness)\n• Gastric discomfort, nausea, or vomiting\n• Flu-like symptoms\n• Dizziness or light-headedness\nWhat to Do\nIf you suspect a person is having a heart attack, call EMS/9-1-1 and get an\nAED immediately. 3. If the person takes a prescribed\nmedication to relieve chest pain\n(e.g., nitroglycerin), offer to\nlocate the medication and help\nthe person to take it.\n• If the person has\nnitroglycerin in a spray or\npill form, ensure that the\nperson sprays or places the\nnitroglycerin under his or\nher tongue.\n4. Reassure the person. Anxiety\nmay increase the person’s\ndiscomfort.Care\n1. Have the person rest comfortably.\n2. If acetylsalicylic acid (ASA) is available, encourage the person\nto chew 160 to 325 mg (either 1 adult-dose or 2 low-dose ASA\ntablets), unless the person has an allergy or a contraindication\nto ASA, such as a bleeding disorder. Ensure that the person\nthoroughly chews and swallows the ASA. Do not repeat the\nNot everyone experiences chest pain during a heart attack.\nCirculation Emergencies52",
