    "content": "Epinephrine\nEpinephrine is a drug that slows or stops the effects of anaphylaxis. If\na person has a risk of experiencing anaphylaxis, he or she may carry an\nepinephrine auto-injector (a syringe system that contains a single dose\nof epinephrine). Different brands of epinephrine auto-injectors may be\navailable, but all work in a similar fashion. Some have audio prompts to\nguide the user.\nDifferent auto-injectors contain difference doses based on the weight of\nthe person (0.15 mg for children weighing between up to 30 kg (66 lb.),\nand 0.3 mg for children and adults weighing more than 30 kg (66 lb.)).\nMany healthcare providers advise that people with a known history of\nanaphylaxis carry at least two doses of epinephrine (two auto-injectors)\nwith them at all times. This is because more than one dose may be\nneeded to stop an anaphylactic reaction. The second dose should\nbe administered if the person is still having signs and symptoms of\nanaphylaxis 5 minutes after the first dose.\nBreathing Emergencies84",
